The table demonstrates the overweighted negative effect of pitch angle variations, as indicated by the high magnitudes of their coefficients. Also, the high adjusted R2superscript𝑅2R^{2} values of up to 83%percent8383\% express a strong linear relationship between similarity score and head pose rotation in the Syn-YawPitch dataset.

As Table II demonstrates a strong linear relationship between head poses and similarity scores, this section analyses the effectiveness of our SYP-Lasso model for estimating the FR utility based on variations in yaw and pitch angles. Specifically, we fit an individual SYP-Lasso regression model for each of the evaluated face recognition systems to learn the FR-specific relationships between similarity scores and yaw-pitch angle combinations. We benchmark our approach against 1) the FR-agnostic ISO/IEC-related pose quality estimator introduced in Section 4.1 and 2) four well-established unified quality assessment algorithms: FaceQnet v1 [8], SER-FIQ [9], MagFace [7], and CR-FIQA [54].
